    body: "The Iconoclasm controversy erupted in 726 when Byzantine Emperor Leo III ordered the destruction of religious images, claiming their veneration was idolatrous. For over a century the empire was torn between iconoclasts (image-breakers) and iconodules (image-venerators). Monks and laypeople suffered persecution for defending icons. The Second Council of Nicaea (787) defined that icons may receive veneration (dulia) though not the worship (latria) owed to God alone, because the honor paid to the image passes to its prototype. A second wave of iconoclasm was finally defeated in 843, celebrated as the 'Triumph of Orthodoxy.'",
